Identifying Customer Segments¶

Project¶

There is a company in Germany which performs mail-order sales. It wants to target a marketing campaign to people that are most likely to purchase their products. It asks for help in identifying these groups of people. The goal of this project is to help the company by finding its customer segments.

The company is real and it is a real business case provided by the Bertlesmann Arvato Analytics. This is why the enterprise name is not revealed. Arvato provided real datasets with business data concerning the company's customers. They are not publicly accessible so I can only present here the results of my analysis.

Project outline¶

This project is quite complicated, so here is the outline of what I am going to do.

  1. Data pre-processing

    The dataset needs a fair amount of preprocessing. There are missing data, features that need re-encoding.

  1. Feature transformation

    There is a lot of features, so I will apply PCA to reduce it. Before applying PCA features need to be scaled.

  1. Clustering

    First, I am going to find clusters in general population. Then I will apply the same clustering to the customer population. I want to find clusters that are over-represented among consumers. This will indicate the company's customer profile.

Step 1: Preprocessing¶

Step 1.1: Assess missing data¶

There are obvious missing values that are coded as NaN but as you had a chance to notice, there are also missing values that are encoded with a special value.

Step 1.1.1: Convert missing value codes to NaNs¶

Let's use the fourth column of feat_info to identify the codes for missing value for each column. What I want to do with it is to convert all these values to NaNs. This will make working with missing values much simpler.

In [6]:
# Display all possible entries in the missing_or_unknow column
feat_info['missing_or_unknown'].unique()
Out[6]:
array(['[-1,0]', '[-1,0,9]', '[0]', '[-1]', '[]', '[-1,9]', '[-1,X]',
       '[XX]', '[-1,XX]'], dtype=object)

You can see that the code for missing data can be not only an int, but it also can be a string like 'X'.

I notice even more. The column missing_or_unknown is coded as a string, but its values are actually arrays of integers. To be useful, they need to be parsed into what they are, arrays of integers (except values like 'X' that are really a string).

Let's write a function that will parse these values.

In [7]:
# Helper function that tells if a string contains a digit
def contains_integer(str_val):
    return str_val.replace('-', '').isdigit()

# Convert value of type '[-1,X]' into array like [-1, 'X'] and return it
def get_missing_codes_array(str_val):
    content = str_val.replace('[', '').replace(']', '')
    if content == '':
        array = [] # Default value for str_val representing empty list
    else:
        array = content.split(',') # Produce array
    # Convert any number into int
    for i in range(len(array)):
        if contains_integer(array[i]):
            array[i] = int(array[i])
    return array

Now I can do the actual conversion. I will write it as a function so I can use it later for the customer set.

In [8]:
# Identify missing or unknown data values and convert them to NaNs.
def convert_missing_codes_to_NaNs(dataset):
    for n in range(len(dataset.columns)):
        missing_str_value = feat_info['missing_or_unknown'][n]
        missing_codes_array = get_missing_codes_array(missing_str_value)
        dataset.iloc[:, n] = dataset.iloc[:, n].apply(lambda x: np.nan if x in missing_codes_array else x)
    
# Do the conversion for general dataset
convert_missing_codes_to_NaNs(azdias)

Step 1.1.3: Assess missing data in each row¶

Now I'm going to perform a similar assessment for the rows of the dataset.

But this time the outliers are observations, not the features that you can simply drop and forget. They actually form a population of outliers and it needs evaluation. If the distribution of the other features is the same between the regular subset and the outlier subset, then they can be dropped. But if you notice that other features are distributed differently in this group, then it means that they form a distinct population that should be analyzed separately.

Let's see how missing data is distributed among observations.

# Identify outliers
def get_outlier_rows(dataset, threshold = 8):
    missing = get_missing_row_counts(dataset)
    # add index, in other case a line below it would use values (counts) and read them as indexes
    outlier_indexes = missing[missing > threshold].index
    # if it is to be a filter, add a copy, without it, it would be just a view
    return dataset.iloc[outlier_indexes].copy()

Step 1.2: Select and Re-Encode Features¶

Algorithms work with numerical data and features that are not encoded numerically will need to be re-encoded. Let's take a look at the kinds of variables in the dataset:

  • numeric features

    They need no action and can stay the way they are.

  • ordinal features

    They are numeric but ordinal indicates that they are evenly spaced (not continous). It means that if a variable is of type 1 - 10, where 1 means 'completely disagree' and 10 means 'completely agree', value of 6.43 has no interpretation. However, you can always approximate 6.43 to 6 and say that it means 'slightly agree'. I'm going to make this simplifying assumption and treat them as numeric.

  • categorical features

    They can be one-hot encoded (converted into a set of binary variables, each one for each category).

  • mixed features

    They are of special kind. They can contain information about two or more features. You can re-encode them into a few separate variables if necessary.

Let's see how many variables of each kind are there.

I'm going to take a look at only non-outlier features since I have removed them from the dataset already. At this point it makes sense to create a copy of feat_info that will include information only about non-outlier features. I will name it reduced_feat_info and will use it from now on.

Step 1.2.1: Re-Encode Categorical Features¶

Categorical variables can be one of two types, binary or multi-level. Multi-level categorical variables need re-encoding. Binary variables need re-encoding only if they are not already encoded numerically.

I'm going to take a closer look at them now.

In [21]:
# Extract categorical variables
categorical_variable_names = reduced_feat_info.loc[reduced_feat_info['type'] == 'categorical']['attribute'].values

# Split them into binary and multi-level
binary = pd.DataFrame(columns = list(['column_name', 'is_string']))
multi_level = []

for column_name in categorical_variable_names:
    unique_values = azdias[column_name].unique()
    n_unique_values = len(unique_values)
    
    # correct for NaN
    if (any(pd.isnull(unique_values))):
        n_unique_values -= 1

    if (n_unique_values == 2):
        is_string = any([isinstance(x, str) for x in unique_values])
        binary = binary.append({'column_name' : column_name, 'is_string' : is_string}, ignore_index = True)
    else:
        multi_level.append(column_name)

# Re-encode OST_WEST_KZ
def re_encode_ost_west_kz(dataset):
    dataset['OST_WEST_KZ'].replace({'W': 1, 'O' : 0}, inplace = True)

Binary variables are ready. Now I only need to apply one-hot encoding for multi-level ones.

One-hot encoder assumes that data contains no missing values, so I will impute the missings first, with the most frequent value.

In [24]:
# One-hot encode given variables, impute them first
def one_hot_encode(dataset, variables):
    # Impute variables with mode first
    for class_name in variables:
       dataset[class_name].fillna(dataset[class_name].value_counts().index[0], inplace = True)
    # Re-encode variables using hot-one encoding
    re_encoded = pd.get_dummies(dataset, columns = variables)
    return re_encoded

Step 1.3: Create a cleaning function¶

Here I'm going to create a cleaning function that I can use to clean the general or the customer dataset without re-running the previous cells again.

My intention is for both datasets to have the same structure. That's why I will remove exactly the same outlier features from both datasets. I will also use the same threshold for outlier rows and apply the same re-encoding of the variables.

In [43]:
def clean_data(input_dataset):
    dataset = input_dataset.copy()
    # Replace missing codes with NaNs
    convert_missing_codes_to_NaNs(dataset)
    # Drop outlier features
    drop_outlier_features(dataset)
    # Drop outlier rows
    dataset, outlier_rows = split_dataset_by_missing(dataset)

    # Re-encode categorical variables
    re_encode_ost_west_kz(dataset)
    dataset = one_hot_encode(dataset, multi_level)

    # Drop or re-engineer mixed type variables
    drop_lebensphase(dataset)
    re_engineer_pj(dataset)
    re_engineer_wohnlage(dataset)
    re_engineer_cameo(dataset)
    drop_baumax(dataset)
    
    return (dataset, outlier_rows)

Step 2: Feature transformation¶

Step 2.1: Apply feature scaling¶

Here I'm going to standardize the features before applying PCA. You can do it in a few ways.

The default strategy is to replace the missing values with an average. The dataset contains many categorical variables, for this reason I'm going to impute the lacking data with the most frequent value.

You can also impute the data before or after scaling. If I impute the data first, then the distribution will preserve the standardized mean and standard deviation. On the other hand if I needed to add many new values to the set before standardization, they would influence its results significantly. I'm going to impute first, because after removing the outliers there are not that many missing values.

In [45]:
# Fit imputer to the general population

    imputed = imputer.transform(dataset)
    return pd.DataFrame(imputed, index = dataset.index, columns = dataset.columns)

# Draw a scree plot associated with the principal components 
def scree_plot(pca):
    num_components=len(pca.explained_variance_ratio_)
    ind = np.arange(num_components)
    vals = pca.explained_variance_ratio_
 
    plt.figure(figsize=(14, 7))
    ax = plt.subplot(111)
    cumvals = np.cumsum(vals)
    ax.bar(ind, vals)
    ax.plot(ind, cumvals)
    for i in range(num_components):
        ax.annotate(r"%s%%" % ((str(vals[i]*100)[:4])), (ind[i]+0.2, vals[i]), va="bottom", ha="center", fontsize=12)
 
    ax.xaxis.set_tick_params(width=0)
    ax.yaxis.set_tick_params(width=2, length=12)
 
    ax.set_xlabel("Principal component")
    ax.set_ylabel("Variance explained (%)")
    plt.title('Explained variance per principal component')

# Plot 15 postive and negative strongest correlations of the principal component with their weights
def pca_results(dataset, pca, component):
    
    MAX_VARIABLES = 15

    # PCA components
    components = pd.DataFrame(np.round(pca.components_, 4), columns = dataset.keys())

    # Take the component by index
    weights = components.iloc[component - 1]

    # Sort it by the weights
    weights = weights.sort_values(ascending = False)
    
    # Get top and bottom weights
    top_weights = pd.DataFrame(weights[:MAX_VARIABLES])
    bottom_weights = pd.DataFrame(weights[-MAX_VARIABLES:])
    
    # Get range for Y
    min_y = min(bottom_weights.values) - 0.05
    max_y = max(top_weights.values) + 0.05

    # Create a bar plot visualization
    fig, (ax1, ax2) = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize = (14, 8))
    
    # Plot the feature weights as a function of the components
    top_weights.T.plot(ax = ax1, kind = 'bar');
    ax1.set_ylabel("Feature Weights")
    ax1.tick_params(which='both', bottom = False, top = False, labelbottom = False)
    ax1.set_ylim(min_y, max_y)
    ax1.legend(loc = 'lower center', ncol = 2)
    ax1.set_title("Positive")
    
    bottom_weights.T.plot(ax = ax2, kind = 'bar');
    ax2.set_ylabel("Feature Weights")
    ax2.tick_params(which='both', bottom = False, top = False, labelbottom = False)
    ax2.set_ylim(min_y, max_y)
    ax2.legend(loc = 'upper center', ncol = 2)
    ax2.set_title("Negative")
    
    fig.suptitle('Strongest correlations of PC{}'.format(component))

Step 3: Clustering¶

Step 3.1: Apply clustering to general population¶

Now I'm going to divide the general population into clusters. Because there is quite a lot of observations, it can take a while. I will use MiniBatchKMeans algorithm to make it more efficient. The algorithm performs clustering in batches and I was wondering what batch size should I type. Then I found this example and determined that they used a batch size of 45 for 3 000 observations. After a quick calculation I came up with a batch of 10 000.

K-means requires you to set the number of clusters beforehand. I want to find the optimum number, so I am going to examine a range of different values. I will plot each model's score against k - the number of clusters. Score is the sum of squared distances between the points within each group. If it is low, it means that the groups are concise. This essentially is what makes the clustering good.

In [57]:
# Calculate a k-means score for a given k
def get_kmeans_score(data, k):
    # Instantiate k-means
    kmeans = MiniBatchKMeans(n_clusters = k, batch_size = 10000, random_state = 42)

    # Then fit the model to the data
    model = kmeans.fit(data)
    
    # Obtain a score related to the model fit
    score = np.abs(model.score(data))
    
    return score

# Calculate the scores for k values between 1 and 30
centers = list(range(1, 31))
scores = list()

for i in centers:
    scores.append(get_kmeans_score(general_X_pca, i))
In [58]:
# Plot the results and investigate them
plt.plot(centers, scores, linestyle='--', marker='o', color='b');
plt.xlabel('K');
plt.ylabel('SSE');
plt.title('SSE vs. K');

Using this plot you want to find the elbow point. It is the point at which further increasing of k brings such a small decrease in distances that it is no longer justified. Essentialy you look for a point at which there is a drop and after that, the curve flattens.

There are a few potential elbow points. It seems to me that the decrease from intial 1.25 at k = 1 to 1.0 at k = 9 seems justified. After this point, the curve flattens. Actually, I could also consider k = 5, but I believe that this number would be too small for customer segmentation and it wouldn't give satisfying results.

Let's refit the model to obtain 9 clusters. I will consider these 9 groups of people in the final analysis.

In [59]:
# Re-fit the k-means model with the selected number of 9 clusters
kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters = 9)
model = kmeans.fit(general_X_pca)

# Obtain cluster predictions for the general population
general_clustering = model.predict(general_X_pca)

Step 3.3: Compare customer data to general data¶

Now is the time for the final step. I am going to compare the distributions of people between the customer and general data. If a whole society was a customer base of the company, you would expect the distributions to be the same. However it likely won't be the case.

Let's say that there is a cluster B that contains 10% of society. If 20% of customers belong to this cluster then it is an anomaly which means that this group is especially attracted to the company. They would rather respond well to the advertising. On the other hand, if only 5% of customers belonged there then it would mean that this group is not that interested in company's products. They rather wouldn't respond well to the marketing.

I'm going to plot both distributions.

  • I will include the outliers group (that I've excluded before) and plot them as a cluster 0.
  • I will use density plot to account for different population sizes

# Increase cluster indexing by 1, so the clusters start at 1, not 0
# Add to the clustering a number of zeros that is equal to the number of outliers
# It will make the histogram to include outliers as a cluster 0
def clustering_with_outliers(clustering, outliers):
    return np.insert(clustering + 1, len(clustering), np.zeros(len(outliers)))

# Get a subset of column names with a few missing values
def get_few_missings_column_names(dataset, threshold = 0.2):
    missing = get_missing_column_counts(dataset)
    few_missing_column_names = [missing.index[i] for i in range(len(missing)) if missing[i] <= threshold]
    return few_missing_column_names

# Print the difference

# Plot distributions of selected two features, side by side, for two outlier populations
def plot_features_distribution_for_outlier_groups(arr_of_two_feature_names, first_bins = [1, 1]):
        
    # Data for each plot
    distributions = []
    for feat_name in arr_of_two_feature_names:
        distributions.append([
            general_outliers[feat_name], 
            customers_outliers[feat_name]
        ])

    # Number of bins for each plot
    n_bins = []
    for feat_name in arr_of_two_feature_names:
        # Equal to the number of classes + one (for displaying)
        n_bins.append(
            np.maximum(
                general_outliers[feat_name].nunique(), 
                customers_outliers[feat_name].nunique()
            ) + 1
        )

    # Bins for each plot
    bins = []
    for i in range(2):
        # Subtract 0.5 so the bars are centered around bins
        bins.append(np.arange(first_bins[i], first_bins[i] + n_bins[i]) - 0.5)

    # Labels
    labels = ['general', 'customers']
    
    # There will be two plots, one by one
    fig, (ax1, ax2) = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize = (16, 4))
    
    ax1.hist(distributions[0], bins[0], label = labels, density = True)
    ax1.locator_params(nbins = n_bins[0])
    ax1.legend(loc='upper right')
    ax1.set_title(arr_of_two_feature_names[0])
    
    ax2.hist(distributions[1], bins[1], label = labels, density = True)
    ax2.locator_params(nbins = n_bins[1])
    ax2.legend(loc='upper right')
    ax2.set_title(arr_of_two_feature_names[1])

Step 3.4: Results of the analysis¶

To sum up my findings, I have found two promising target groups and two groups that should be avoided in marketing efforts.

The company's customers are mainly high and top earners. First group includes peaceful young idealists that care about social well-being. They like to attend events and could be targeted there. Second part has families and cares about environment. They could be targeted where they live, in city centers, or online as they are highly active there.

There are two customer segments that should be avoided as they are especially under-represented among customers. One part can be described as low earning residents of low status city districts. The second segment are single, non-mainstream males with a kind of rebellious attitude.
